"Walk me through the most complex architectural decision you made in the last year."
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A legacy Java application built as a single, unified codebase  Spring, Struts, all business logic, data access, and user interface code are tightly coupled and deployed together as one application.
In my last project, we needed to redesign to support rapid feature development and handle increased traffic.

The most complex architectural decision was choosing between a full microservices migration or a modular monolith approach.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
I led a technical analysis with the team. We considered factors like team experience, deployment automation, data consistency, and operational overhead.
A full microservices migration offered scalability and independent deployments, but would require significant investment in DevOps, distributed tracing, and inter-service communication.
A modular monolith would allow us to refactor the codebase into well-defined modules with clear boundaries, enabling parallel development and easier future migration to microservices.
After prototyping and stakeholder discussions, we chose the modular monolith approach. We established clear module boundaries, enforced them with build tools,
and gradually extracted a few services where independent scaling was critical (e.g., notifications, reporting). This decision balanced delivery speed, maintainability,
and future scalability. It also minimized risk and allowed the team to build DevOps maturity before a full microservices transition.
This experience taught me the importance of aligning architecture with business needs, team capabilities, and long-term goals—rather than just following trends.


"How do you handle security vulnerabilities found in third-party libraries?"
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Monitor dependencies using automated tools (e.g., Dependabot, Snyk, OWASP Dependency-Check, npm audit, Maven’s versions plugin) to get alerts about known vulnerabilities.
Assess the severity and exploitability of the vulnerability—review CVE details, affected features, and whether your usage is impacted.
Upgrade the affected library to a patched version as soon as possible. Test thoroughly to ensure compatibility.
If an upgrade isn’t immediately possible, apply mitigations: disable vulnerable features, use workarounds, or restrict access.
Track and document the vulnerability, mitigation steps, and upgrade plans.
Regularly review and update dependencies to minimize risk.
Educate the team on secure dependency management practices.



